description:
Aim:&nbsp; Study of hyperuricemia a prognostic marker in chronic kidney disease.&nbsp; Methods:&nbsp; This cross-sectional study was carried out in the Department of Medicine, Darbhanga Medical College and Hospital, Laheriasarai, Darbhanga, Bihar, India.&nbsp; Results: &nbsp;100 patients were included in this study. The prevalence of hyperuricemia amongst our study participants was 65% (95% CI: 58.3&ndash;75.7%). On bivariate analysis, patient&rsquo;s age (&beta;: 0.54, 95% CI: 0.25&ndash;0.84), eGFR (&beta;: -0.67, 95% CI: -0.91 &ndash; -0.43), CKD stage 4 (&beta;: 20.55, 95% CI: 10.32&ndash;30.76) or CKD stage 5 (&beta;: 20.82, 95% CI: 9.55&ndash;32.09), spot urine PCR (&beta;: 3.76, 95% CI: 1.12&ndash;6.40), severe proteinuria (&beta;: 16.51, 95% CI: 6.56&ndash;26.46), no hypertension (&beta;: -17.83, 95% CI: -27.17 &ndash; -8.48), systolic (&beta;: 0.25, 95% CI: 0.09&ndash;0.40) and diastolic (&beta;: 0.58, 95% CI: 0.14&ndash;1.01) blood pressures, diabetes (&beta;: 9.01, 95% CI: 0.87&ndash;17.14), low protein diet (&beta;: -8.31, 95% CI: -16.07 &ndash; -0.55), low-Carb diet (&beta;: 8.36, 95% CI: 0.64&ndash; 16.07), ULT (&beta;: 22.71, 95% CI: 16.00&ndash;29-42), loop diuretics (&beta;: 11.94, 95% CI: 3.75&ndash;20.13), body mass index (&beta;: 1.06, 95% CI: 0.07&ndash;2.05) and no anaemia (&beta;: -27.42, 95% CI: (&minus; 39.02 &ndash; -15.82) were significantly associated with serum uric acid. Mean serum uric acid significantly differed across CKD stages (F: 7.91, p value &lt; 0.001) severity of proteinuria (F: 5.46, p value = 0.006) Also, on bivariate logistic regression, patient&rsquo;s age (OR: 1.05, 95% CI: 1.02&ndash;1.09), eGFR (OR: 0.93, 95% CI: 0.89&ndash; 0.96), CKD stage 4 (OR: 9.11, 95% CI: 2.01&ndash;33.21) or CKD stage 5 (OR: 6.67, 95% CI: 1.63&ndash;27.27), spot urine PCR (OR: 1.52, 95% CI: 1.01&ndash;2.30), severe proteinuria (OR: 4.71, 95% CI: 1.59&ndash;13.99), no hypertension (OR: 0.06, 95% CI: 0.01&ndash;0.30), systolic (OR: 1.03, 95% CI: 1.01&ndash;1.06) and diastolic (OR: 1.05, 95% CI: 1.00&ndash;1.11) blood pressures, low protein diet (OR: 0.42, 95% CI: 0.18&ndash;0.98), low fat diet (OR: 3.09, 95% CI: 1.06&ndash;9.02), ULT (OR: 6.71, 95% CI: 2.32&ndash;19.37), loop diuretics (OR: 3.73, 95% CI: 1.29&ndash;10.82), obesity (OR: 6.65, 95% CI:1.36&ndash;32.61) and no anaemia (OR: 0.04, 95% CI: 0.00&ndash; 0.29) were significantly associated with hyperuricemia. On multivariate analysis, after adjusting for patient&rsquo;s age, eGFR, spot urine PCR, systolic blood pressure, ULT, loop diuretics and haemoglobin level, patient&rsquo;s age (&beta;: 0.49, 95% CI: 0.24&ndash;0.74), eGFR (&beta;: -0.36, 95% CI: -0.57 -0.16), CKD stage 4 (&beta;: 17.49, 95% CI: 9.52&ndash;25.45) or CKD stage 5 (&beta;: 13.28, 95% CI: 4.41&ndash;22.16), spot urine PCR (&beta;: 3.06, 95% CI: 1.09&ndash;5.04), severe proteinuria (&beta;: 13.94, 95% CI: 4.92&ndash; 22.95), no hypertension (&beta;: -18.37, 95% CI: -28.67 -8.06), systolic (&beta;: 0.14, 95% CI: 0.02&ndash;0.25) and diastolic (&beta;: 0.35, 95% CI: 0.03&ndash;0.66) blood pressures, ULT (&beta;: 18.84, 95% CI: 12.98&ndash;24.71), loop diuretics (&beta;: 6.62, 95% CI: 0.25&ndash;12.99) and no anaemia (&beta;: -18.08, 95% CI: (&minus; 27.55 -8.61) were significantly associated with serum uric acid.&nbsp; Conclusions: &nbsp;Hyperuricemia was independently associated with patient&rsquo;s age, eGFR, spot urine PCR, hypertension, ULT, loop diuretics, obesity and anaemia. 
